          "body": "The chapter opens with a grammatical and theological collision: 'the sons of Israel acted unfaithfully... for Achan... took some of the things under the ban.' The entire nation is indicted in the first clause; an individual is named in the second. This is not imprecision — it is the covenant solidarity of Israel under the Mosaic economy. The ban (*cherem*) was not merely Achan's constraint; it was the whole community's. When he took it, he infected the whole. The defeat at Ai (7:4-5) is the first visible consequence: thirty-six dead, the army routed, the hearts of the nation 'melted and became as water.' The melting hearts are the chapter's bitter irony — this language was used of the Canaanites' fear at Israel's approach (Joshua 2:11; 5:1); now Israel itself is reduced to the terror that was supposed to belong to its enemies. Secret sin does not remain private. It drains the community of its capacity to stand."
