          "body": "The execution at the Valley of Achor (7:24-26) is among the most disturbing passages in Joshua and requires honest engagement. Achan's sons, daughters, livestock, and household goods are brought with him and destroyed. The Deuteronomic law in 24:16 prohibits children dying for fathers' sins — a tension that commentators resolve in various ways. The most defensible reading, given the narrative's insistence that the stolen items were found in Achan's tent (7:21-22), is that the household was complicit in the concealment, making them participants in the *cherem* contamination rather than innocent bystanders. The point is not that children routinely die for fathers — Deuteronomy 24:16 stands — but that in this instance the household shared in the sin that made them *cherem*. The heap of stones raised over Achan (7:26) is the same memorial marker raised over the king of Ai after the subsequent victory (8:29). Both are buried under stones; both are monuments to God's governance of the conquest. Yet the Valley of Achor does not remain a symbol of judgment in the canon. Hosea 2:15 declares that God will give the Valley of Achor as 'a door of hope' in the day of Israel's restoration. Isaiah 65:10 makes it a pasture in the new creation. The site of Israel's worst covenantal failure becomes the address of eschatological hope — the place of the curse becomes the threshold of the promise."
